{{Short description|American painter}} {{Infobox artist | name = Betsy Graves Reyneau | image = Photo of Artist Betsy Graves Reyneau.jpg | imagesize = | caption = {{small|Artist Betsy Graves Reyneau and AACP president Thomas L. Griffith standing besides portrait of Dr. [[George Washington Carver]], 1948}} | birth_name = | birth_date = 1888 | birth_place = [[Battle Creek, Michigan]] | death_date = 1964 | death_place = [[Camden County, New Jersey]] | nationality = [[United States|American]] | movement = [[Photorealism]] | awards = | patrons = | field = [[Portrait painting]] | training = [[School of the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]] | works = | influenced by = | influenced = }}
'''Betsy Graves Reyneau''' (1888–1964) was an [[United States|American]] painter, best known for a series of portraits of prominent [[African American]]s once owned by the [[Harmon Foundation]]. [[Mary McLeod Bethune]], [[George Washington Carver]], [[Joe Louis]], and [[Thurgood Marshall]] were among her sitters.
== Early life == Reyneau was raised in [[Detroit]], and although discouraged by her father from becoming an artist on the grounds that it was inappropriate for a woman, she broke ties with the family to pursue that career, and as a young woman attended the [[School of the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]]. She later lived in France for a time before returning to the United States and becoming active in civil rights causes. She was later selected by the Circuit Court of Detroit, unbeknownst to her family, to paint a portrait of her grandfather, Michigan Supreme Court Justice [[Benjamin F. Graves]]. Reyneau was also a [[suffragette]]; she became, in 1917, one of the first woman to be arrested and imprisoned for protesting [[Woodrow Wilson]]'s stance on women's voting rights.<ref name="Fifteen">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oyaxYvSG6gAC|title=After the Vote Was Won: The Later Achievements of Fifteen Suffragists|last=Adams|first=Katherine H.|last2=Keene|first2=Michael L.|publisher=McFarland|year=2010|isbn=9780786456475|location=|pages=57–67}}</ref>
== Legacy == Many of Reyneau's portraits are currently in the collection of the [[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]] of the [[Smithsonian Institution]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://npg.si.edu/object/npg_NPG.67.81|title=Aaron Douglas|last=|first=|date=|website=National Portrait Gallery, Smithsonian Institution|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-08-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://npg.si.edu/object/npg_NPG.67.77|title=Richmond Barthe|last=|first=|date=|website=National Portrait Gallery, Smithsonian Institution|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-08-01}}</ref> She was inducted into the [[Michigan Women's Hall of Fame]].
